{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_hastings_ver02/data/sn95047334/00529042413/1938010601/0002.xml":{"full_text":"Page Two\nToo Late\nTo Classify\nBy\nRUSSELL KAY\nIt\u2019s tunny where a guy will get\nan idea sometimes. Here I was\nsttfing at my typewriter trying to\nfigure what to write for this\nweek\u2019s column and my so-called\nmind as blank as the page before\nme. I began spinning a coin on the\nedge of my desk as I courted the\nelusive muse.\nThen I forgot the column and be\ncame absorbed in the coin. It was\nan old one, a half dollar, worn\nnearly smooth. I could make out\nthe familiar eagle with outstretch\ned wings. I knew the banner he\nheld in his beak was inscribed \u201cE\nPluribus Uniim\" but that legend\nhad totally disappeared. The tops\nof the letters that had spelled\n\u201cHalf\u201d and \u201cDollar\u201d were still\nfaintly visible. The \u201cUnited States\nof America\u201d and most of the stars\nwere gone.\nThen I turned it over to deter\nmine the date. I couldn\u2019t make it\nout for sure. It was 1891 or it\nmight have been 1881. Above \u201cLi\nberty\u2019s\u201d faint head I could barely\nmake out the-remnants of a letter\nhere and there I knew once read\n\u201cIn God We Trust.\u201d\nAnd I wanted to laugh. What a\nmotto for a nation that didn\u2019t trust\nanybody, much less an Unknown\nDeity. Then suddenly it didn\u2019t seem\nfunny at all; it became a tragedy.\nHere was a nation favored be\nyond any other; wealthy, prosper\nous,/-peaceful, where living stand\nards, advantages and opportuni\nties surpass those found anywhere\nelse: young, powerful, free. A\nleader in education, science, indus\ntry and progress\u2014and yet it seem\ned to lack something and then I\nasked myself the same question\nmillions of others are asking;\n\u201cWhat\u2019s wrong with the country?\u201d\nYou know all the answers as\nStrength During\nMIDDLE LIFE\nStrength is extra-important for\nwomen going through the change of\nlife. -Then the body needs the very\nbest nourishment to fortify it against\nthe changes that are taking place.\nIn such cases, Cardui has proved\nhelpful to many women. It in\ncreases the appetite and aids diges\ntion, favoring more complete trans\nformation of food into living tissue,\nresulting in improved nutrition and\nbuilding up and strengthening of\nthe whole system.\nELECT\nSruce Davis\nTO GROUP ONE\nFLORIDA RAILROAD\nCOMMISSION\nSubject to Democratic Primaries\nin May\nYOUNG CAPABLE\nENERGETIC\nLET US HELP YOU\nBE COMFORTABLE\nTHIS WIHTER\nImagine the pleasure of a warm\ncomfortable home this winter\u2014\nthe benefit to the health and hap\npiness of your family. Your heat\ning system should be checked\nnow before the cold weather sets\nin. We shall be glad to repair your\nboiler or show you the advan\ntages and economies of replac\ning it with a Crane efficient heat\ning system. Ask us.\nCharles G. Diehl\nTelephone 14 Quincy, Fla.\nwell as I do if you read your news\npaper, listen to the radio, or talk\nto your neighbor. But those an\nswers are all different and not one\nof them is correct.\nThe President and his followers\ntell us big business is to blame.\nBig business retaliates by bring\ning the same charge against Mr.\nRoosevelt and the administration.\nLabor points an accusing finger at\ncapital; capital denounces labor.\nCo-called 100 per cent Americans\nthump their manly chests and\ncurse the foreign born. Democrats\nblame the Republicans and Repub\nlicans the Democrats \u2014and so it\ngoes. We elect min to govern, then\nbelittle their efforts and question\ntheir motives. No one whose views\ndiffer from ours is entitled to\neither respect or consideration.\nFrom an upright God-fearing na\ntion of industrious men and wo\nmen we seem to be developing into\na nation of cliques and groups, each\nselfish in its own interest, intoler\nant, distrustful, greedy\u2014all eager\nto tear down and no one capable\nof building.\nAnd the pitiful part of it is\nthere isn\u2019t anything wrong with\nthe country. The only thing wrong\nis the people who live in it. High\nand low, rich and poor, native or\nforeign born, we are all in the\nsame degree to blame.\nAmerica does not owe her\ngrowth and her glory to any par\nticular group or class or creed.\nAmerica is a composite picture of\nevery man, woman and child that\nmakes up its citizenship and the\nsolution to its problems as well as\nits future lies in the hearts and\nminds and thoughts and actions of\nALL.\nThe little negro that sucks at its\nmammy\u2019s breast in the scrub is\njust as much an AMERICAN as\nyou or I; the Jew is just as much\nan AMERICAN as the Gentile.\nThe mingled blood of black and\nwhite, Jew and Gentile, makes up\nthe dust in Flanders Fields, only\na lot of us have forgotten.\nWhen we as INDIVIDUALS re\nstore our faith in each other;\nwhen we work with and for eacn\nother; when we each turn our at\ntention first to what\u2019s wrong with\nourselves; when we become toler\nant enough to respect Americans,\nregardless of race, creed or color,\nand engrave in our own heart,\n\u201cIn God We Trust\u201d\u2014then we will\nhave solved the Nation\u2019s REAL\nproblem. The answer to what\u2019s\nwrong with the country will be\nfound in the mirror\u2014yours and\nmine.\nLet\u2019s hope that \u201cUnited States\nof America\u201d and \u201cIn God We\nTrust\u201d will not disappear from\nthe face of the earth as they did\nfrom that time-worn coin:\nI Greensboro\nMr. and Mrs. E. W. Cowen and\nchildren were dinner guests Sun\nday of Mr. and Mrs. W. D. Fer\nguson.\nMr. and Mrs. Carl Green spent\nSunday in Camilla, Ga., with Col.\nand Mrs. J. D. Gardner.\nCol. J. D. Gardner and Judge\nMose Warren of Camilla, Ga.,\nand Burnette Moore of Sparta,\nGa., visited friends and relatives\nhere Saturday.\nHarry Wells, Rachel Green and\nCarl Green, Jr., spent the week\nend in Camilla, Ga., with Col. and\nMrs. J. D. Gardner.\n1 Bertelle Fletcher, Jr., and Win\nton Green have returned to the\nUniversity of Florida, Gainesville,\nafter spending the holidays with\ni their parents.\nMisses Kathleen Strange of Con\ncord, Betty Fellows of Panama\nCity, Annie Muriel Smith of Jen\nnings, Sara Lee of Midwav o-\nHoward, of ^a., Corinne Van\nIderstine, of Lakeland and Frances\nTubb of Waverly, Tenn., have re\nturned to Greensboro where they\nare teachers, after having spent\nthe Christmas holidays with rela\ntives.\nMrs. H. B. Boyd and family are\npreparing to make their future\nhome in Webster, where H. B.\nBoyd is preparing to enter the\ngrocery business.\nMrs. Eloise Featherstone re\nturned to her home in Miami Sun\nday, after several days\u2019 visit with\nher parents, Dr. and Mrs. 0. W.\nGardner.\nDr. V. W. Fletcher, wife and\nchildren, of Ringgold, La., spent\nChristmas holidays with Mr. and\nMrs. E. B. Fletcher.\nDr. E. B. Fletcher and family\nhave returned to their home in\nLeesburg, after having spent the\nholidays with Mr. and Mrs. E. B.\nFletcher.\nMr. and Mrs. C. M. McLean and\ndaughter, Elizabeth, and Mrs.\nGrace Tutt, of Tallahassee, Mrs.\nByron Ellinor of Havana and Miss\nVivian Cumbie of Lake City spent\na while with Mrs. F. A. Cumbie\nSaturday afternoon.\nMiss Hilda Hines returned to\nTallahassee Sunday, after spend\ning the holidays with her parents,\nMr. and Mrs. B. H. Hines.\nMr. and Mrs. Lynn Perry of\nCamilla, Ga., spent a while here\nTuesday.\nWHO KNOWS?\n1. How many industrial unions\nare aligned with the C. I. 0. 1\n2. How much is the mileage al\nlowance for members of Con\ngress\n3. What is the estimated loss in\nstock values during the present\nmarket slump?\n4. When will the Ludlow Reso\nlution come to a vote in the\nHouse?\n5. What is the most common\nname in the United States?\n6. How much did the WPA\nspend during 1937?\n7. Can a farm tenant get Gov\nernment aid in the purchase of\na farm?\n8. What is the highest post in\nthe Navy.\n9. How many men are now cov\nered by \u201cjobless insurance?\u201d\n10. What is the value of our\ncommerce with Japan?\nSlated Fot 1940?\nNo sooner had ex-Governor Alfred\nM. Landon called at the White\nHouse to exchange pleasantries\nwith the President, then an\nnounced to the press he would not\nconsider the 1940 Republican\nnomination, than GOP leaders saw\na sudden boom for George D.\nAiken, Governor of Vermont, as\na possible candidate. Governor\nAiken (above), who resembles\nLandon slightly, modestly dis\nclaimed presidential aspirations,\nsaid, \u201cI don't know what I\u2019ve done\nto deserve it.\u2019\u2019\nIHlMHint#!\nnwA\nmimno mouJEi-i-\nProblems of 1938: Several ma\njor questions loom upon the 1938\nhorizon. They are going to have\nto be answered.\nThe most vital problem is whe\nther we can avoid being smeared\nwith war entanglements, either in\nAsia or in Europe.\nPresident Roosevelt has taken\nthe position that he earnestly de\nsires peace and will exert every\neffort to that end, but that, in the\nmeantime, our Army, Navy, and\nMarine Crops will be well equipped\nand ready to protect our national\nintegrity if necessary.\nBig Navy and Business: The\nnew Navy building program will\nbe used to take up unemployment.\nThe percentage of labor cost in\nnaval vessel construction is high.\nAlso, the heavy goods industry\nwill respond quickly to the use of\nsteel and armaments.\nBusiness Recession: The so-call\nbusiness recession presents a prob\nlem second in importance to the\nwar question.\nThe sentiment for immediate ac\ntion on the tax situation is grow\ning and it can, with reasonable\ncertainty, be assumed that the\nWays and Means Committee will\npresent a bill in the early days of\nthis session.\nUnemployment: Then there is\nthe more and more pressing mat\nter of unemployment. No one\nknows exactly how serious it is.\nThe Unemployment Census, re\ncently taken, is the best index, but,\nadmittedly, it is far from accur\nate. Estimates run all the way\nfrom three to seven million unem\nployed.\nFarm Relief: The passage of\nfarm bills by the Senate and House\nin the special session did not by\nany means solve the prob\nlem MC one yet knows just what\nsort of legislation the conferees\nwill agree upon but, since they\nmust confine their consideration to\nmatter presented in one of the\nother of the bills before them, we\nknow it will not provide the relief\nthe farmers so badly need.\nThe backbone of successful ag\nriculture in the Southeast is di\nversification. The so-called money\ncrops are of course absolutely ne\ncessary, but the farmers\u2019 efforts\nmust not be devoted entirely to\nthem. The Boileau amendment, put\non the bill in the House, and, in\nsubstance, added in the Senate,\nprecludes the payment of benefits\non lands taken from the money\ncrops and planted to dairy, poul\ntry, and market crops.\nFlorida consumes more milk than\nit produces and the domestic mar\nket offers much to the Florida\ndairymen. Whether the conferees\ncan eliminate the Boileau amend\nment is doubtful but, unless it is\ndone, the bill will penalize this\narea.\nThe tobacco section of the Farm\nBill, as passed by both Senate and\nHou~e, materially curtails new\nproduction of the flue-cured pro\nduct. Although the exact amount\nto be allotted to each county, and\nto each farmer within the county,\ncannot yet be definitely ascertain\ned, it is apparent that the allot\nments will be disappointingly\nsmall.\nNorth Against South: Unfor\ntunate though it is, we seem to\nbe experiencing another term of\nNorth against South. The anti\nlynch bill is aimed directly at this\nsection. The wages and hours bill\nwas sponsored by the Northern\ninterests for the expressed pur\npose of keeping Northern industry\nfrom moving Southward. The farm\nbill, in some respects, has a decid\ned Northern complexion.\nNOT SO MYSTERIOUS\nHuntingon, Ind.\u2014An attractive\n\u201cmystery\u201d woman was taken into\ncustody by police upon the find\ning of threatening pencil notes on\na telegraph sheet. She was re\nleased after she revealed she had\nbeen reading a detective magazine\nand that the notes on the tele\ngram were made to aid in solving\nthe murder mystery problem.\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES\nDavis Announces\nAs Candidate for\nR.R. Commission\nTallahassee, Jan. 6.\u2014Bruce Da\nvis today made formal announce\nment of his candidacy for a four\nyear term on the Florida\nCommission, Group 1, subject to\nthe Democratic primaries to oe\nheld in May.\nDavis said he would base, his\ncampaign on a P r <^am of return\ning the administration of the Com\nmission to the people of the state\nin an \u201copen door\u201d policy that would\nassure full public knowledge of all\nCommission transactions.\n\u201cIt is time that the people of\nFlorida know something about this\nunit of their state government,\nDavis said in a prepared statement.\n\u201cIn past.years, a general indiffer\nence to public sentiment has mark\ned Commission members\u2019 activi\nties, with the exception of the six\nmonths\u2019 campaign time each four\nyears.\n\u201cThe Florida Railroad Commis\nsion spends approximately $50,000\nof the taxpayers\u2019 money each year,\nbut not one in ten people can give\nan inkling of how the money is\nspent.\n\u201cI shall make my campaign on\nthe principle that Floridians are\nentitled to full knowledge of the\ntransactions and proceedings of\nthe Railroad Commission; that\neach citizen of Florida is entitled\nto receive full, open and above\nboard representation in the matter\nof regulating rates for rail, bus,\ntruck and telephone sendee.\n\u201cIt is my firm conviction that\nthe Railroad Commission offices\nand works should be open for the\ngeneral education and enlighten\nment of the public and should not\nbe, as apparently has been the\ncase in the past, the particular and\nindividual knowledge of a small\ngroup of office and job holders in\ndifferent to public welfare.\n\u201cI am making this campaign be\ncause I feel the people of Florida\nare entitled to sane and sensible\nrepresentation as in other units of\ngovernment.\u201d\nFlat Creek\n\nMrs. Cora Shelter and son of\nBaldwin spent last week here\nwith Mrs. Ruth Shepard and other\nrelatives.\nMiss Hilda Clark left Saturday\nfor Jacksonville after spending a\nweek here with her parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. C. A. Clark.\nMrs. S. W. Dean and Clyde\nDean of Chattahoochee visited at\nMr. and Mrs. C. A. Clark\u2019s Satur\nday afternoon.\nMr. and Mrs. E. W. Cowen and\nchildren of Savannah, Ga., spent\nthe week end here with relatives\nand friends.\nMiss Ruby Clark spent Sunday\nwith Mr. and Mrs. Audie Clark.\nMrs. Elma Daniels left Wednes\nday for her home in Tavares af\nter spending some time here visit\ning relatives.\nMr. and Mrs. M. N. Smtih, Mrs.\nElma Daniels and Mr. and Mrs.\nAudie Clark were dinner guests\nMonday of Mr. and Mrs. Joseph\nSuber of Sawdust.\nMrs. Hugh Vanlandingham and\u2019\nchildren of Juniper spent Tuesday\nwith Mr. and Mrs. C. A. Clark. I\nMr. and Mrs. Edwin Clark and\nchildren and Mrs. Lorene Mears\nspent Monday with A. B. Smith and\nfamily.\nByTCh fcubanks of Columbus,\nGa., visited Mr. and Mrs. J. T.\nKelly and Misses Willie and Dome\nSmith Tuesday.\nMr. and Mrs. Kerr of Rhine, Ga.,\nand Mr. and Mrs. Ben Kerr of Tai-,\nlahassee visited Mr. and Mrs. J. TJ\nKelly and Misses Willie and Don-;\nnie Smith Wednesday. j\nPaul Smith and Miss Velma\nGlenn of Sycamore were married\nDecember 24. We extend to this\ncouple hearty congratulations and\nbest wishes.\nFor quality printing patronize\nthe Times Office.\nTHERE IS NO\n^ubititute\nFOR MONEY IN THE BANK\nMen and women often suffer heavy losses\nin making investments. They play with\nfuture uncertainties which seem to\npromise joy and profit, but which too\noften deliver only grief and loss.\nAfter all, there is no substitute for\nmoney in the bank, which today offers\nsecurity and certainty, instead of un\nCertainty. Money in the bank is readily\navailable; it is protected by the bank's\nown resources, with the added protec\ntion of Federal Deposit Insurance up to\n$5,000 for each depositor.\n\nCitizens Bank Trust Co.\nQUINCY FLORIDA\nThere is No Substitute for Money in the Bank\nProvidence\nMr. and Mrs. Pleas Rhoden of\nPensacola are on a two week B va\ncation among relatives and friends\nin this section of the state. Mrs.\nRhoden will be remembered as\nMiss Annie McCoiman, this com\nmunity being her former home\nEri Dean, Mr. and Mrs. Alton\nDean and son, James Neal, of\nJacksonville spent New Year s with\nrelatives here, at Orange and\nJohn Hunt and Edd Barrow, of\nMt. Vernon, Ga., spent last week\nwith Rev. G. T. Hunt.\nDecember 16, Charles Rudd, Bb,\nof Elba, Ala., died at his home.\nHe was bom in the Wetumpka\ncommunity, near here, and was a\nstep-son of Mrs. Mollie Rudd of\nQuincy. Two surving daughters\nare Mrs. Laura Hudson and Mrs.\nAllie Tinner of Elba, Ala., one\nbrother, Miles Z. Rudd, Providence,\nfour half sisters, Mrs. Mandie\nRichards, Providence, Mrs. Alice\nGray, Miss Thursey Rudd of Quin\ncy and Mrs. Jackie Craven of We\ntumpka.\nMiss Helen Cox spent Sunday\nwith Misses Gladys and Susie\nRichards.\nMaxwell Strom has recently\nbeen remodeling and adding to his\nhome. x\nMaxwell Fletcher left the first\nof the week for Gainesville where\nhe is a student.\nClub members spent the day\nworking at Glen Julia Thursday on\ntheir project.\nLee Edwards left recently to\nspend a few days in South Florida\nwith relatives.\nMr. and Mrs. Howell Dean of\nChattahoochee were among rela\ntives here and Antioch Thursday\nafternoon. Miss Estelle Dean re\nturned home with them, after\nspending a few days with her\ngrandmother, Mrs. Craven, at An\ntioch.\nMrs. J. E. Jones left Sunday\nmorning to visit her sister at Capi\ntola.\nMidway\nMr. and Mrs. J. T. Smothers\nspent New Year\u2019s day with Mr.\nand Mrs. J. B. Kirkland.\nMrs. Ethel Haslop of Tampa\nspent the holidays with Mr. and\nMrs. Corbett Kirkland.\nMiss Louise Richardson of Jack\nsonville spent some time with Mrs.\nOra Hale recently.\nA. J. Reese left for Southern\nCollege, Lakeland, accompanied by\nhis mother, Mrs. L. Reese.\nMiss Irene Branch of Tallahas\nsee spent some of the holidays\nwith Misses Thelma and Opal Foot\nman.\nEmmett Ferrell left for the\nUniversity of Florida after spend\ning the holidays with Mr. and Mrs.\nJ. P. Ferrell.\nFred Murray, Jack Timmons,\nWarren McGriff of Jacksonville\nspent the week end with Hayden\nSmith.\nMiss Techla Smith of Jackson\nville spent the week end with her\nparents, Mr. and Mrs. Smith and\nfamily.\nMiss Inez Mullins has accepted\na position in the hospital at Chat\ntahoochee.\nThe many friends of Mr. and\nMrs. Russell Bowers are sorry to\nlearn that they are moving away\nfrom our community.\nJ Miss Marie Harrison was a vis\nitor here Saturday.\nJ Mrs. R. A. Walters, Mrs. Jack\nShelfer and Misses Gladys Har-\nI ris and Bertha Bloodworth spent\nSaturday afternoon with Mrs. L.\nReese and Mrs. Lucy.\nGOITRE\nMake This Quick Test: Get a\nsmall bottle Sorbol-Quadruple, a\ncolorless liniment. For simple goitre\napply twice daily. It quickly sup\nplies substance needed by the thy\nroid gland. Thousands have been\nrelieved. Get more information at\nCity Drug Store. Note: Mrs. F. H.\nBaker, Box 246, Dunedin, Fla., says,\n\u201cI was relieved 14 years ago. I will\ntell or write my experience to any\none.\"\np>IF>H\nnew A A A AJ\nAll Sizes \u2014Particularly Suitable for IrrigW\nL. A. Rocco 1\nPHONE 30 QUINCY, F\nWe Have on Hand a Supply\nGood Farm Mid\nSEE US BEFORE YOU BUY\nSuber Johnson Stockyard\nQUINCY, FLORIDA\nSTATE THEATRE 1\nTHURSDAY ONLY\nBRIAN AHERNE\u2014OLIVIA DeHAVILLAM\nin\n\u201cThe GREaI\nGARRICK\u2019\nALSO SELECTED SHORTS\nfuh\u00ae\nGROWIM\nr o w eI\nI\nIn every bag of Armour\u2019s Big Crop\nFertilizer there\u2019s a balanced ration of\ngrowing power all those elements^\nboth major and minor, that your to*^\nbacco, cotton, corn and general field\ncrops require.\nOpen a bag examine the fertilizo^j\nSee how uniform it is. You can tell\nlooking at it that Armour\u2019s Fertilizer m\nready to go to work